{"at": "2026-06-05T01:44:34Z", "commit_ref": "none", "intent": "feature-list", "actor": "user", "kind": "input", "content": "We are going to work on Optical Constructor UI. I will give you some sketches and your task is to analyze current code and specs, look up the web for similar apps, check the ideas, and then expand that text below into a feature list. The list below is incomplete, so do your best.\n\nCurrent main screen becomes the “legacy” form available via the legacy menu item. It is a good illustration of what’s available.\n\nThe main screen layout. I think that Word / Excel have a very good layout structure: top menu switches the ribbons, the ribbons provide controls of what is relevant to the current task. But, if the ribbon is hidden, then the menu becomes a fully expanded menu, which allows doing everything that the ribbons allow. \n\nHere are some general comments\n\nLanguages EN / RU (saved into settings). Both must be supported. All pairs of strings must be in some centralized place for ease of maintenance. JSON, YAML, or something like that file, which will be consumed at run time AND can be edited to change the strings / add languages. The system must check that nothing is missing and default to some English text and show the error message at startup, which would allow the user to copy it.\nUnits of measure – m, cm, mm, mkm, nm, A, and in in case somebody wants them. A lot was written about them in previous specs. There are no changes here.\nStandardize controls – single place to describe. If a new flavor of controls is needed (e.g. a button of different color), then it is added there and changes to the least of properties that are needed to make the control stand out are made.\nCheck all the proposed buttons / mouse actions below, advise if that could be improved.\nDCLK – opens element dialog.\nRIGHT CLICK – menu: element dialog, local help, ???.\nCTRL+Z – undo. More than one level is needed.\nCTRL+Y – redo\nSHIFT+R (with confirmation) – resets the element to its standard rotation (R1 = 0, R2 = 0, R3 = 0).\nF1 – local help – show help about selected object (what the controls do) – a pop up window.\nESC – close local menu.\nActive element must be shown so that it is clear that it is an active element. All actions happen ONLY with the chosen (active) element.\nCome up with some other hotkeys if they make sense.\n\nActive element – that’s the element that is currently selected.\nElement – 3 angles of rotation: rotation around primary normal to the element (R1 – this needs clarification if the light ray is a horizontal line from the left to the right, then R1 is a rotation around that line), rotation around normal to the table (R2), rotation around R1 x R2 (R3, very rarely used, must be unlocked first).\nMOUSE LEFT PRESS + MOVE on element DOES NOT DO anything because it is very easy to do.\nSHIFT + MOUSE LEFT PRESS + MOVE – moves PP (see below) along CR. See the OT for its specifics.\nSHIFT + MOUSE WHEEL –R1, step 5 degrees (in config), if not locked, \nCTRL + MOUSE WHEEL –R2, step 5 degrees (in config), if not locked\nALT + MOUSE WHEEL – R3 (must be unlocked first), step 5 degrees (in config)\nEach element must show the value of R1, R2, R3 nearby, clicking on that must allow editing the values by hand (and have a reset button for each of all rotations). R3 is locked by default. The user may lock / unlock any of the rotations (with the current values) to prevent changes.\n\nOptical Table (OT) – the place where all the editing happens. Default view is from the top and in most of the cases this is all that we need. The table is selected when the user clicks on anything that is NOT an optical element (see below).\nMouse LEFT PRESS + MOVE – moves the table with all elements on it.\nMouse wheel - zoom in / out.\nRotations of the table just changes the view and so all elements “travel” with the table. R1, R2, R3 for the table are relative to the screen. There must be an easy way to reset the view to (0, 0, 0).\n\nOptical Element (OE) – the basic unit in the optical constructor.\nThere are two special ones: light source (LS) and photo detector (PD), check the name. A light source draws three parallel lines: the central ray (CR) and 4 side rays, two left / right and two top / bottom (above CR and so coincide with CR when viewed from the top and when there are no element that will “unhide” them) (all together - the ray group, (RG)). The side rays are only important when lenses, non-flat mirrors, prisms / wedges, etc. are used. All elements except mirrors produce transmitted T and reflected R ray groups (TRG and RRG). Mirrors produce only RRG. This is only at the level of the metadata attached to the OE – any element can be configured to ignore R or T but not both. Mirrors are placed with T turned off, all other elements are places with whatever they are configured to turn off, if any. Turning off the second one automatically turns on the other one. The PD terminates the RG. The light falling on an element is called incident light (IRG). Any RG falling on the element is IRG from that element point of view. Each element has a placement point (PP). PP of each element snaps to CR or IRG. If some element is rotated in such a way that RG after the element changes the direction, then PP “travels” with the CR. All element rotations are ALWAYS measured in relation to IRG CR. So, if e.g. RRG changes direction due to some element rotation, then all the elements on the way change their place because the PP snaps in and then a rotation relative to IRG also snaps in.\n\nWe need to agree on how to trace the rays when any element is rotated so that R2 and or R3 are not null. The drawing on the table is a schema. So, we use standard n = 1 outside, n = 1.5 inside and then use Snell’s law to draw the lines.\n\nWe need to agree on the standard elements. These are the names on the table. For example, a light source could be a green laser OR a mercury lamp. This is still an LS on the optical table. Here are some proposed names\nOptical Table (OT)\nLight Source (LS)\nLinear Polarizer (LP)\nCircular Polarizer (CP)\nSample (S)\nPhoto Detector (PD) – but check the name\n\nExperiment collection – a set of experiments around the same material or materials, called sample / samples. The collection exists to make it convenient to easily “turn” on / off elements in the experiment.\n\nElement Group – one or more optical elements that we can easily place / remove on the way of the CR. There is always a primary CR path (but we can put in more PDs if really necessary). The groups are blocks on the way of the CR or CRs if we place multiple PDs. For example, here is a typical experiment:\nLS => Group 1 (Nothing or LP1 or CP1) => Group 2 (Nothing or S1 or S2 or S1 + S2) => Group 3 (Nothing or LP2 or CP2) => PD\nThe users should be able to quickly assemble the experiment out of chosen pieces. The experiment could be repeated because the conditions have changed.\n\nPD – if more than one, then the user must be able to choose the primary one."}
{"at": "2026-06-05T01:44:34Z", "commit_ref": "none", "intent": "spec", "actor": "agent", "kind": "decision", "content": "Authored .feature-list-md for the Optical Constructor UI: Office-style ribbon/menu shell with legacy form, EN/RU centralized editable strings with startup completeness check, standardized controls, optical table view/navigation, optical-element model (R1/R2/R3 rotations with per-axis lock and reset, active-element clarity), ray model (LS ray group, CR + side rays, RRG/TRG, mirror RRG-only, PD termination, PP snapping, n=1/n=1.5 Snell schematic), standard element catalogue, reviewed and extended mouse/keyboard scheme, element groups and experiment assembly, experiment collections, multi-level undo/redo, local help; flagged open questions (PD name, R1 axis, Ctrl+wheel-vs-zoom, ribbon tabs, schematic conventions).\n"}
